      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "# Lee, let's talk about this knee\n\nFirst — I'm really glad you brought this up rather than just pushing through it. Sharp pain that's been around for two weeks and shows up on stairs is your body sending a clear signal, and it deserves to be taken seriously.\n\nI have to be straight with you here: **diagnosing what's causing that pain is genuinely outside my lane as a coach.** Sharp knee pain with a specific pattern like stair descent — that's exactly what a physiotherapist or sports medicine doctor is trained to evaluate. They can actually examine the joint, rule out structural issues, and give you a real answer. I'd be doing you a disservice if I guessed at a cause and got it wrong.\n\nOn the ibuprofen question specifically — that's a medical decision, and I'd want you to run that by a doctor or pharmacist rather than me. Taking anti-inflammatories before runs to mask pain can sometimes mean you're training through damage you can't feel, which tends to make things worse over time. That's the coaching concern, but the medical call isn't mine to make.\n\nAnd on shortening runs to keep going — I hear the instinct, because stopping feels like losing ground. But here's the honest coaching perspective: **two weeks of sharp pain is a reason to pause, not modify around.** Running through it without knowing what's happening risks turning a manageable issue into a longer setback. The half marathon is July 11th — you have real time to get this assessed, recover properly, and still build a strong block.\n\n---\n\n**What I'd suggest as a next step:**\n\nGet in front of a physio or sports medicine professional as soon as you can — ideally this week. When you go, mention the IT band history from last year, because that context may be relevant to them.\n\nOnce you have clearance and a clearer picture, I'm ready to rebuild your plan around whatever timeline and constraints make sense. You've been putting in consistent, quality work — the fitness you've built doesn't disappear in a recovery window.\n\n**What does your access to a physio or sports medicine doc look like right now — is that something you can arrange fairly quickly?**"
        }
      ],
      "messageId": "msg_019ejuX5xbY4DFji9abRgMyQ"
    }
